General understanding of data/files¶

  • We have 4 files in total
    • calendar.csv
      • Rows Count:- 7966127
      • Columns Count:- 7 (listing_id, date, available, price, adjusted_price, minimum_nights, maximum_nights)
    • listings.csv
      • Rows Count:- 21825
      • Columns Count:- 75 (id, listing_url, scrape_id, last_scraped, source, name, description, neighborhood_overview, picture_url, host_id, host_url, host_name, host_since, host_location, host_about, host_response_time, host_response_rate, host_acceptance_rate, host_is_superhost, host_thumbnail_url, host_picture_url, host_neighbourhood, host_listings_count, host_total_listings_count, host_verifications, host_has_profile_pic, host_identity_verified, neighbourhood, neighbourhood_cleansed, neighbourhood_group_cleansed, latitude, longitude, property_type, room_type, accommodates, bathrooms, bathrooms_text, bedrooms, beds, amenities, price, minimum_nights, maximum_nights, minimum_minimum_nights, maximum_minimum_nights, minimum_maximum_nights, maximum_maximum_nights, minimum_nights_avg_ntm, maximum_nights_avg_ntm, calendar_updated, has_availability, availability_30, availability_60, availability_90, availability_365, calendar_last_scraped, number_of_reviews, number_of_reviews_ltm, number_of_reviews_l30d, first_review, last_review, review_scores_rating, review_scores_accuracy, review_scores_cleanliness, review_scores_checkin, review_scores_communication, review_scores_location, review_scores_value, license, instant_bookable, calculated_host_listings_count, calculated_host_listings_count_entire_homes, calculated_host_listings_count_private_rooms, calculated_host_listings_count_shared_rooms, reviews_per_month)
    • listings2.csv
      • Rows Count:- 21825
      • Columns Count:- 18 (id, name, host_id, host_name, neighbourhood_group, neighbourhood, latitude, longitude, room_type, price, minimum_nights, number_of_reviews, last_review, reviews_per_month, calculated_host_listings_count, availability_365, number_of_reviews_ltm, license)
    • reviews.csv
      • Rows Count:- 573077
      • Columns Count:- 6 (listing_id, id, date, reviewer_id, reviewer_name, comments)

In this particular file, we are going to analyze the reviews of AirBNB. We'll work with NLP and will try to find the reviews sentiments.

Before moving forward, we need to clean our reviews as some of the reviews are in different languages so before processing the sentiments, we need to translate them.
For easy cleaning, we will define a function which takes text as input and gives the output by translating it to english and then we will use it further in code before processing it for sentiments.
And, first we will get the comments which are not in english

In [7]:
# Function to detect language and return the result
def process_translation(comment):
    try:
        detected_language = detect(comment)
        if detected_language == 'en':
            return comment
        else:
            return None
    except Exception:
        return None

        translation = translator.translate(text, "English")
        return translation.result
    except Exception as e:

        return text

# saved_file_path = './Data-AirBNB/processed_reviews.csv'
saved_file_path = './Data-AirBNB/reviews_sents.csv'

if os.path.exists(saved_file_path):
    reviews = pd.read_csv(saved_file_path)
    print("Loaded saved sentiment analysis data.")
else:    
    # Creating an object of Sentiment Intensity Analyzer
    analyser = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    
    # Function to get the compound score from polarity_scores
    def get_compound_score(review):
        return analyser.polarity_scores(review)['compound']
    
    # Parallelizing the sentiment analysis using joblib
    reviews['compound'] = Parallel(n_jobs = -1)(
        delayed(get_compound_score)(x) for x in tqdm((reviews['comments']), desc = "Processing Reviews")
    )
    
    # Classifying sentiments based on the compound score
    reviews['sentiment'] = np.where(reviews['compound'] >= 0.05, 'positive', 
                                    (np.where((reviews['compound'] < 0.05) & (reviews['compound'] > -0.05), 'neutral', 'negative')))
    
    
    
    reviews.to_csv(saved_file_path, index = False)

Cleaning Comments¶

In [18]:
# Getting all the stop words (english)
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# Creating an object for Lemmatizer (eg:- change/changing/changed/changes --> change)
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

# Function to  perform the cleaning
def clean_comments_text(text):
    try:
        # Lowering the text
        text = text.lower()
    
        # Regular Expression for removing non-alphabetic characters (except space)
        text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]', '', text)
    
        # Tokenizing the words
        words = word_tokenize(text)
    
        # Checking and getting rid of any stop word
        negative_words = ['not', "n't", 'wasn\'t', 'weren\'t', 'couldn\'t', 'no', 'nor', 'don\'t', 'doesn\'t', 'isn\'t']
        words = [word for word in words if word.lower() not in stop_words or word.lower() in negative_words]
    
        # Lemmitization
        words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in words]
    
        # Concating all the tokens into one sentence (clean text)
        clean_text = ' '.join(words)
        
        return clean_text
    except:
        return text

reviews_sent = reviews_sent.dropna(subset = ['comments']).reset_index(drop = True)

)

# Join all cleaned comments into one string
text = ' '.join(neg_reviews['CleanedComments'])

# List of words to remove
words_to_remove = ['would', 'could', 'even', 'stay', 'place', 'living', 'complaint', 'day', 'location']

# Split text into words and generate bigrams
words = text.split()
bigrams = ngrams(words, 2)

# Filter out bigrams that contain any of the words to remove
filtered_bigrams = [' '.join(bigram) for bigram in bigrams if not any(word in words_to_remove for word in bigram)]

# Count the frequency of bigrams
bigram_counts = Counter(filtered_bigrams)

# Generating the word cloud from the bigram frequencies

As we can clearly see the above output that positive class is over 500k whereas the negative and neutral classes are in thousands only. This is a class imbalance issue. If we train our model with this data, it will become biased to positive class and the accuracy will drop.
Although, we have a lot of ways to tackle the class imbalance problem but due to limited resources we will apply the simplest technique where we'll take sample out of the positive reviews. The sample's shape will be same as negative or neutral reviews.

In [25]:
# Segregating the original dataset

neg_df = imb_data[imb_data['sentiment'] == 'negative'].reset_index(drop = True)
pos_df = imb_data[imb_data['sentiment'] == 'positive'].reset_index(drop = True)
neu_df = imb_data[imb_data['sentiment'] == 'neutral'].reset_index(drop = True)
In [26]:
# Taking a sample for positive reviews out of 500K+ records

pos_df = pos_df.sample(n = len(neg_df), random_state = 42)
In [27]:
# Combining all the datasets & shuffling them

combined_df = pd.concat([neg_df, pos_df, neu_df], ignore_index = True)
bal_data = combined_df.sample(frac = 1, random_state = 42).reset_index(drop = True)

In [48]:
# Function - converting to Torch Dataset for compatability

class SentimentDataset(torch.utils.data.Dataset):
    def __init__(self, encodings, labels):
        self.encodings = encodings
        self.labels = labels

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.labels)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        item = {key: torch.tensor(val[idx]) for key, val in self.encodings.items()}
        item['labels'] = torch.tensor(self.labels[idx])
        return item
In [49]:
# Converting to Torch Dataset

# Function - Compute Metrics

def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    logits, labels = eval_pred
    predictions = torch.argmax(torch.tensor(logits), dim = -1).numpy()
    
    # Calculate precision, recall, f1-score, and accuracy
    precision = precision_score(labels, predictions, average = 'weighted')
    recall = recall_score(labels, predictions, average = 'weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(labels, predictions, average = 'weighted')
    accuracy = accuracy_score(labels, predictions)
    
    # Return all metrics
    return {
        'precision': precision,
        'recall': recall,
        'f1_score': f1,
        'accuracy': accuracy
    }

# Function - Highlighting the row
def highlight_max_r2(max_idx, min_idx):
    def highlight(s):
        return [
            'background-color: lightgreen' if i == max_idx 
            else 'background-color: lightcoral' if i == min_idx 
            else 'background-color: lightcyan' 
            for i in range(len(s))
        ]
    return df_metrics.style.apply(highlight, axis = 0).applymap(lambda _: 'font-weight: bold;', subset = [df_metrics.columns[0]])

In [100]:
# Function - To predict the output

def predict_sentiment(text):
    # Tokenizing the input text
    encodings = tokenizer(text, padding = 'max_length', truncation = True, max_length = 128, return_tensors = "pt")
    
    # Moving the encodings to the correct device (CPU)
    encodings = {key: val.to(load_device) for key, val in encodings.items()}
    
    # Making prediction
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(**encodings)
        logits = outputs.logits

    # Getting the predicted class (0 = Negative, 1 = Neutral, 2 = Positive)
    predicted_class = torch.argmax(logits, dim = -1).item()

    # Mapping the predicted class to the sentiment
    if predicted_class == 0:
        sentiment = "Negative"
    elif predicted_class == 1:
        sentiment = "Neutral"
    else:
        sentiment = "Positive"
    
    return sentiment
In [101]:
# Different sentences to cover example of each class while predicting
sentences = [
    "This movie was a complete waste of time.",
    "I had a regular day at work.",
    "The food at the restaurant was amazing, highly recommend it.",
]

# Passing each sentence one-by-one
for sent in sentences:
    # Running the Model Function to get the sentiment
    sentiment = predict_sentiment(sent)
    print(sent)
    print(sentiment, end = '\n\n')

Model Comparison¶

In this analysis, we compared the performance of five different models: Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Naive Bayes, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and BERT. The following metrics were used to evaluate the models: Accuracy, Average Precision, Average Recall, and Average F1-Score for all models.

1. Logistic Regression:¶

  • Accuracy: 87.53%
  • Average Precision: 87.85%
  • Average Recall: 87.55%
  • Average F1-Score: 87.66%

Logistic Regression shows solid performance with an Accuracy of 87.53%. It maintains a good balance across all metrics, with precision, recall, and F1-score all close to each other, reflecting consistent results. However, it still falls short compared to more complex models like Random Forest and BERT.

2. Random Forest:¶

  • Accuracy: 88.31%
  • Average Precision: 88.36%
  • Average Recall: 88.37%
  • Average F1-Score: 88.34%

Random Forest outperforms Logistic Regression with an Accuracy of 88.31%, demonstrating excellent precision, recall, and F1-scores. It offers a solid improvement in performance, showcasing the advantage of ensemble methods in improving predictive accuracy for sentiment classification.

3. Naive Bayes:¶

  • Accuracy: 82.46%
  • Average Precision: 82.52%
  • Average Recall: 82.68%
  • Average F1-Score: 82.51%

Naive Bayes, while performing adequately with an Accuracy of 82.46%, continues to be the least effective among the models. Although its precision, recall, and F1-score are consistent, it lags behind in comparison to the more sophisticated models like Random Forest and BERT.

4. Support Vector Machine (SVM):¶

  • Accuracy: 87.37%
  • Average Precision: 87.58%
  • Average Recall: 87.42%
  • Average F1-Score: 87.49%

SVM shows decent performance with an Accuracy of 87.37%, comparable to Logistic Regression but slightly behind Random Forest. The model demonstrates a good balance of precision, recall, and F1-score, but is not quite as accurate as the top performers like Random Forest or BERT.

5. BERT:¶

  • Accuracy: 92.42%
  • Average Precision: 92.56%
  • Average Recall: 92.42%
  • Average F1-Score: 92.42%

BERT leads with the best performance, achieving an Accuracy of 92.42%. The model excels across all metrics with the highest precision, recall, and F1-score, confirming its ability to effectively capture the subtleties of sentiment in reviews. This high performance makes BERT the standout model for sentiment analysis.

Summary:¶

  • BERT performed the best with the highest accuracy of 92.42%, along with superior precision, recall, and F1-scores, making it the most effective model for sentiment analysis.
  • Random Forest came in second with an Accuracy of 88.31%, showing strong overall performance and excellent balance across all metrics.
  • Logistic Regression performed well with an Accuracy of 87.53%, but was outperformed by both Random Forest and BERT.
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM) showed solid results with an Accuracy of 87.37%, performing similarly to Logistic Regression but still not as good as the top models.
  • Naive Bayes had the lowest accuracy of 82.46%, showing that while it is a simple model, it is not as effective as the other models for this task.

Conclusion: Based on the evaluation metrics, BERT is the best-performing model for sentiment analysis, offering the highest accuracy and superior results across all metrics. Random Forest also shows strong performance but is outpaced by BERT. The traditional models (Logistic Regression, SVM, and Naive Bayes) perform well, but their accuracy and overall effectiveness are lower compared to the deep learning-based BERT model.

Marketing Strategies¶

1. Existing Hosts:¶

Benefit of Using the Sentiment Analysis Model: Existing hosts can use the sentiment analysis model to gain valuable insights into guest feedback, helping them understand the sentiment behind reviews and improve their services. By analyzing the reviews automatically, they can identify the key areas of improvement or areas where they excel, enabling them to enhance guest satisfaction and stay competitive in the market.

How It Can Help:

  • Identifying Strengths and Weaknesses: By classifying reviews as positive, negative, or neutral, the model allows hosts to quickly pinpoint which aspects of their property guests appreciate most (e.g., cleanliness, amenities, location) and which need improvement (e.g., communication, responsiveness).
  • Improving Customer Service: Understanding the sentiment of reviews enables hosts to address common concerns in negative or neutral reviews, ultimately leading to better guest experiences and higher ratings.
  • Targeted Marketing: By analyzing positive reviews, hosts can highlight their top-rated features (e.g., proximity to attractions or superior service) in their marketing materials, drawing attention to aspects that resonate most with guests.

2. Potential Guests:¶

Benefit of Using the Sentiment Analysis Model: Guests can use the sentiment analysis model to evaluate the general tone of reviews for a property they are considering, helping them decide if the listing meets their expectations based on past guests’ experiences.

How It Can Help:

  • Review Confidence: By analyzing reviews, guests can get a clear picture of the overall guest experience through sentiment insights, making it easier to trust the feedback and decide if the listing aligns with their needs.
  • Targeted Property Search: Guests can use sentiment insights to filter listings with the most positive reviews or identify properties that consistently receive feedback in line with what they value, such as comfort, cleanliness, or location.
  • Avoiding Negative Surprises: The sentiment model can help guests identify negative patterns in reviews, ensuring they avoid properties with consistent complaints regarding cleanliness, poor service, or misrepresented amenities.

3. New Hosts:¶

Benefit of Using the Sentiment Analysis Model: New hosts can use the sentiment analysis model to gather actionable insights from early reviews of their listings. This helps them understand how their property is being received by guests, allowing them to make data-driven adjustments to improve their offering.

How It Can Help:

  • Learning from Guest Feedback: By analyzing both positive and negative reviews, new hosts can quickly adjust to meet guest expectations. For example, if feedback suggests poor communication, they can improve their response times or provide clearer instructions.
  • Building a Strong Reputation: New hosts can use sentiment insights to refine their property presentation and guest interactions to ensure they maintain a positive sentiment in reviews from the outset, building a strong reputation.
  • Improving Guest Experience: The model helps new hosts focus on the most critical guest concerns identified in negative or neutral reviews, allowing them to prioritize and resolve issues that could affect their future bookings.
